From: nvidia-driver-injector <noreply@example.invalid>
Date: 2026-05-12
Subject: [PATCH 0004/0007] tb-egpu: PCIe error handlers + recovery state machine (cluster P2)

Consolidates these legacy patches into one coherent recovery cluster:

  0007 — register nv_pci_err_handlers with the kernel AER subsystem
  0016 — recovery state struct + work_handler + sysfs scaffolding
  0017 — probe-time WPR2-stuck detection
  0023 — S1 portion only: tb_egpu_dump_aer_trigger_event helper +
         the call site in nv_pci_error_detected
         (S2/DIAG-AER2 portion deferred to P6 — see "Deviations" below;
          S3 already landed in P3)
  0024 — H1 (MaxAttempts), H2 (rate-limit), H3 (kill-switch file),
         post-rmInit-FAIL trigger, slot_reset + slot_reset_resume,
         force_trigger sysfs, killswitch file
  0026 — additional sysfs force_trigger surface
  0027 — explicit slot_reset / slot_reset_resume dispatch from the
         work handler
  0028 — attempt_count semantics correction (reset only at post-rmInit-OK)
  0029 — err_handlers parts only: mmio_enabled + cor_error_detected
         callbacks (close-path safety in 0029 belongs to P4)

Inventory items applied (per docs/patch-refactor-inventory.md "### P2"):

- Rename map applied wholesale:
    Lever-M / lever_m              -> recover
    TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_*         -> TB_EGPU_RECOVER_WPR2_*
    NVreg_TbEgpuLeverM*            -> NVreg_TbEgpuRecover*
    tb_egpu_lever_m_*              -> tb_egpu_recover_*
    /var/lib/aorus-egpu/lever-m-killswitch
                                   -> /var/lib/tb-egpu/recover-killswitch
    files nv-lever-m-recover.{c,h} -> nv-tb-egpu-recover.{c,h}
    field nvl->lever_m             -> nvl->recover

- Gate logic deduplicated. The H1/H2/Enable gate evaluation was
  previously duplicated between trigger_post_rminit_fail and
  nv_pci_error_detected. Extracted to:

      enum tb_egpu_recover_gate {
          TB_EGPU_RECOVER_GATE_OK = 0,
          TB_EGPU_RECOVER_GATE_DISABLED,
          TB_EGPU_RECOVER_GATE_RATE_LIMITED,
          TB_EGPU_RECOVER_GATE_SURRENDER,
      };
      enum tb_egpu_recover_gate tb_egpu_recover_pre_schedule_gates(
          struct tb_egpu_recover_state *st,
          struct pci_dev *pdev,
          const char **reason_out);

  Both call sites switch on the returned enum. The helper takes pdev
  so GATE_SURRENDER can emit PERMANENT_FAIL uevent in-helper rather
  than at both call sites; reason_out is a static string for logging.

- WPR2 read path deduplicated. The ioremap -> ioread32 -> iounmap
  triplet was duplicated 3x (probe-time check, trigger function,
  slot_reset verify). Extracted to:

      int tb_egpu_recover_read_wpr2(u64 bar0_phys, u32 *raw_out);

  Returns 0 on success and stores raw value in *raw_out, or -errno
  on ioremap failure.

- Killswitch file path promoted to a #define:
    TB_EGPU_RECOVER_KILLSWITCH_PATH "/var/lib/tb-egpu/recover-killswitch"

- Sysfs surface consolidated: 5 separate device_create_file pairs
  collapsed to a single static const struct attribute_group plus
  sysfs_create_group / sysfs_remove_group calls (same pattern P3
  established in nv-tb-egpu-qwd.c).

- pdev_for_work race audit: removed the legacy "Defensive: stale
  pdev_for_work" branch (which dropped a pci_dev_put refcount that
  could not exist). Replaced with a WARN_ON_ONCE tripwire inside the
  in_progress=1 guard. Ordering reasoning documented inline:
    * trigger writes pdev_for_work BEFORE schedule_work (publishes)
    * handler clears pdev_for_work BEFORE clearing in_progress
    * atomic_xchg(&in_progress, 1) returning 0 implies handler ran C→D
  The defensive branch was dead — surfaced and removed.

- The AER-capture helper (tb_egpu_dump_aer_trigger_event) is no longer
  EXPORT_SYMBOL — it's nvidia.ko-internal and declared only in the
  project-private nv-tb-egpu-recover.h header.

- Inter-commit chronology comments stripped. "Patch 0024 v1 NOT...",
  "Patch 0028 (2026-05-08): attempt_count is NO LONGER reset here..."
  etc. — design intent kept (one concise comment per invariant), the
  history-of-getting-there belongs in git log.

- Default for NVreg_TbEgpuRecoverEnable: 0 (OFF). Documented inline
  with a TODO marker for the planned post-Phase-3 flip-to-1.

Cross-cluster wire-in:

- One-line call added to P3's tb_egpu_qwd_thread detect path (inside
  the !detected_logged latch in kernel-open/nvidia/nv-tb-egpu-qwd.c):

      tb_egpu_dump_aer_trigger_event(nvl->pci_dev, "qwd-detect",
                                     &qwd->last_aer);

  Populates the qwd->last_aer snapshot exposed by P3's
  tb_egpu_qwd_last_aer_summary sysfs reader. With this wire-in,
  last_aer.valid flips to 1 on first detect and the sysfs reader
  emits the full AER + DPC + link snapshot. Until P3 + P2 are
  stacked, P3 alone reports "(no detection event yet)".

Deviations from inventory (flagged for status doc + future clusters):

- **S2 (DIAG-AER2) portion of legacy 0023 deferred to P6.** S2
  extends tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump, which is introduced by legacy
  0018 — assigned to P6 (diagnostic telemetry surface). The function
  does not exist in P1+P5+P3 baseline; the S2 expansion cannot land
  before its host function. P6 owns: (a) introducing diag_dump from
  0018, (b) the S2 expansion from 0023, (c) re-introducing the
  diag_dump call sites in nv_pci.c's err_handlers callbacks (the
  AER-capture call stays here in P2).

- Legacy 0029's mmio_enabled callback originally invoked BOTH
  tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump AND tb_egpu_dump_aer_trigger_event.
  This patch keeps only the AER call. P6 will add back the
  diag_dump call when it lands the function.

- Gate function got a pdev parameter (not in the original brief).
  Lets GATE_SURRENDER emit PERMANENT_FAIL uevent in-helper. Trade-off:
  helper takes an extra arg vs. duplicating uevent emission at both
  call sites. Single-source-of-truth chosen.

- TB_EGPU_LOG_ONCE from P1's RM-side nv-tb-egpu.h is NOT used in P2
  (kernel-open does not share the RM include path; only one log-once
  site exists in P2). Kept the inline static-int latch pattern; not
  worth a shared kernel-open header for one site.

